full_text: Now homeowners have to separate the electric metering between the main house and basement in order to have a legal ADU. This costs thousands of dollars. Additionally, if the basement ceiling is less than 7', they have to dig it out. This is tens of thousands more.
full_text(utf-8): b"Now homeowners have to separate the electric metering between the main house and basement in order to have a legal ADU. This costs thousands of dollars. Additionally, if the basement ceiling is less than 7', they have to dig it out. This is tens of thousands more."

full_text: BUT, after DC implemented the 2016 ADU rules that policymakers said would make ADUs easier to build, DCRA stopped permitting new kitchenettes (even wet bars!) and new full bathrooms in basements for homeowners who aren't going through the full ADU process.
full_text(utf-8): b"BUT, after DC implemented the 2016 ADU rules that policymakers said would make ADUs easier to build, DCRA stopped permitting new kitchenettes (even wet bars!) and new full bathrooms in basements for homeowners who aren't going through the full ADU process."

full_text: Add a small kitchen and bathroom if necessary, dig out a deep window to provide an escape and more light if the basement doesn't already have adequate fire escapes, and you have a quasi apartment ready to rent out.
full_text(utf-8): b"Add a small kitchen and bathroom if necessary, dig out a deep window to provide an escape and more light if the basement doesn't already have adequate fire escapes, and you have a quasi apartment ready to rent out."

full_text: This provided a relatively cheap and easy way for homeowners to rent out space that offers them and their tenants privacy. Many DC basements have at least a backdoor so they have already their own entrance.
full_text(utf-8): b'This provided a relatively cheap and easy way for homeowners to rent out space that offers them and their tenants privacy. Many DC basements have at least a backdoor so they have already their own entrance.'

full_text: Some of these were (are) illegal and don't meet safety requirements, but some were a legal way of homeowners renting out a room in their house with stairs still connecting the main house and basement apartment and with adequate egress in the basement apartment in case of fire.
full_text(utf-8): b"Some of these were (are) illegal and don't meet safety requirements, but some were a legal way of homeowners renting out a room in their house with stairs still connecting the main house and basement apartment and with adequate egress in the basement apartment in case of fire."

full_text: Prior to 2016 DC already had lots of basement apartments. This is the most feasible way to add ADUs in DC's rowhouse neighborhoods.
full_text(utf-8): b"Prior to 2016 DC already had lots of basement apartments. This is the most feasible way to add ADUs in DC's rowhouse neighborhoods."

full_text: In 2016 DC began officially allowing ADUs in most residential zones to lots of fanfare about new housing supply and affordability.
full_text(utf-8): b'In 2016 DC began officially allowing ADUs in most residential zones to lots of fanfare about new housing supply and affordability.'

full_text: DC's ADU rules are an example of how NOT to do this, which we talked about on the show, but I didn't do a very good job of articulating, so here's the issue.

full_text: The UK experience -- with national-level urban planning but very restrictive zoning and very high house prices -- challenges the idea that higher level governance can be expected to improve housing availability and affordability.
